"&#xa0;\n&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;Submission of the Aerospace Aviation &amp; Defence Knowledge Transfer Network (AAD KTN) to the House of Commons Science and Technology Committee Inquiry on Women in STEM careers&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\nWhy do numbers of women in STEM academic careers decline further up the career ladder?&#xa0;&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\nThe role of mentoring&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\nWidening the pool of applications&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;The pipeline &#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\nTable 1: Total growth in the number of undergraduate students in engineering and technology subjects and the gender split of that growth\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\nOverall growth\nGender split of overall growth\nFemale\nMale\n2010/11 – 2011/12\n6%\n3%\n7%\n2009/10 – 2011/12\n10%\n2%\n11%\n2001 – 2011/12\n5%\n0%\n5%\nSource: Higher Education Statistics Agency, 2013\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\nWhen women leave academia, what careers do they transition into? What are the consequences of scientifically trained women applying their skills in different employment sectors?&#xa0;&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;&#xa0;What should universities and the higher education sector do to retain women graduates and PhD students in academic careers? Are there examples of good practice?&#xa0;&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\nWhat role should the Government have in encouraging the retention of women in academic STEM careers?&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\nConcluding remarks&#xa0;&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n1\n&#xa0;\n The Chemistry PhD: the impact on women’s retention, Jessica \nLober\n Newsome, UK Resource Centre for Women in SET and the Royal Society of Chemistry\n \nGender survey of UK profess\nori\nate, 2013, http://www.timeshighereducation.co.uk/news/gender-gap-in-number-of-female-professors/2004766.article\n \nMentoring Foundation - \nwww.mentoringfoundation.co.uk\n \n \nExtracted from - Table 2.7.2a, which shows the numbers of undergraduate student Full-Time Equivalent in engineering and technology, by sex and HESA cost \ncentre\n, 2001-02 to 2011-12.  Produced by the Higher \nEducation Statistics Agency.\n Engineering and Technology \nSkills &amp; Demand in Industry, Annual Survey 2012\n \nEngineering and Technology Skills &amp; Demand in Industry, Annual Survey 2013\n"